      </div>
      <p>All of these solutions appear extremely daunting, filled to the brim with information. Any user would feel
        reluctant scanning through the poorly formatted text or paying for widely available information. Sexducate seeks
        to alleviate this reluctance by providing the most relevant information packaged in an elegant platform.
      </p>
      <div class = "title">User Research</div>
      <p>With teenagers (ages 13-18) being our largest possible userbase. We faced the problem of attracting and maintaining
        their attention. <span class = "bolded">How could we attract uninterested individuals to our site?</span> Our research
        group consisted of college individuals aged 18-22 and asked questions such as:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>When and what was your first sexually-explicit encounter?</li>
        <li>Have you ever had formal sexual education?</li>
        <li>Have you ever personally researched sexual education?</li>
        <li>What do you believe is the most common STD?</li>
        <li>Do you practice safe sex?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>From these questions, we were able to better understand the interaction between teenagers and sex. Nearly
        every individual first encountered sex through a form of media, whether television or internet, at a relatively
        early age (grades 6-12). Very rarely did an individual personally seek out sexual education, but every individual
        participated in sexual education during school. However, individuals seemed to misunderstand the prevelance of certain
        types of STD's. Many individuals believed more media-pervasive STD's such as AIDS, HIV, Gonorhea represented most common STD's.
        Some even believed very common infections such as Syphillis were non-existent or "cured".
      </p>
      <p>With our research, we were able to make several realizations. The entry-point and proliferation of our website relied
        on the K-12 educational system. We tested several other ideas, such as spreading through social media platforms. Further
        research revealed that many teenagers of the current generation hold social media sacred and integral to social hierarchy
        and interaction. Very few individuals professed interest in retweeting or sharing a website regarding STD information and
        preferred to keep their social media specifically about personal activities. Since every individual participated in a
        sexual education course at one point in K-12, we focused our design on maintaining interest through interactive design.
      </p>
      <div class = "title">Design</div>
      <p>To quickly convey information about STD's, we decided to develop Sexducate as a single-page application. With a SPA,
        we held more control over a user's navigation. Through paper prototyping, I was able to conviently
        collaborate and edit sketches with the team before deciding on a singular design.
      </p>
