      <div class = "title">Development</div>
      <p>As the lead developer of the project, I decided to implement the project using
      HTML5, CSS3, and D3 for our frontend, and NodeJS, Express, and Postgres for our backend.
      I started learning D3 by implementing simple bar graphs but decided to switch to circle graphs
      for better STD percentage visualization. To introduce an interactive feel to our application, I also
      implemented a chloropleth map of the Greater San Diego area. The choropleth map not only provided
      a visual display of all prevalent STD's but also statistical data for each individual area code. Each
      section of the map represents an area code specified in a geoJSON file. By uploading the geoJSON to MapBox,
      I was able to create a static choropleth map of San Diego representing each zip area. After querying my
      Postgres database with Express routing and storing the data in JSON format, I used D3 to request data about
      specific counties for my circle graphs.
